╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  SHIP'S ARCHIVE: grep                                         ║
║  Classification: Core Tool                                    ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

┌─ ORIGIN STORY ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  The name comes from the ed editor command g/re/p - meaning    │
│  "global / regular expression / print". Ken Thompson wrote     │
│  grep overnight on March 3, 1973, to help Doug McIlroy search  │
│  the Federalist Papers for linguistic patterns. It was so     │
│  useful that Thompson extracted it into a standalone tool.     │
│  Brian Kernighan called it a "memorable mini-revolution."      │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ MENTAL MODEL ─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  Think of grep as a FILTER that only lets matching lines       │
│  through:                                                      │
│                                                                │
│     Input Stream          grep "ERROR"          Output         │
│    ┌────────────┐        ┌──────────┐       ┌────────────┐    │
│    │ INFO: ok   │───────▶│          │       │            │    │
│    │ ERROR: bad │───────▶│  FILTER  │──────▶│ ERROR: bad │    │
│    │ INFO: fine │───────▶│          │       │ ERROR: x   │    │
│    │ ERROR: x   │───────▶│          │       └────────────┘    │
│    └────────────┘        └──────────┘                         │
│                                                                │
│  The filter tests each line: does it match the pattern?        │
│  If yes, it passes through. If no, it's discarded.            │
│                                                                │
│  Key flags:                                                    │
│    -i   → case-insensitive (Error = error = ERROR)            │
│    -r   → recursive (search directories)                      │
│    -n   → show line numbers                                   │
│    -v   → invert (show lines that DON'T match)                │
│    -c   → count matches instead of showing them               │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ CONNECTIONS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  • Works well with: pipes, find (-exec), xargs                │
│  • Alternatives: ack, ag (silver searcher), ripgrep (rg)      │
│  • Builds toward: Regular expressions, text processing        │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ ARIA'S INSIGHT ───────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                │
│  "Start simple: 'grep ERROR *.log' finds errors in log files. │
│  Add -i when case doesn't matter. Add -r when you need to     │
│  search directories. The power of grep scales with your       │
│  knowledge of regular expressions - but literal strings work  │
│  perfectly fine for most tasks."                               │
│                                                                │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
